    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Graphical</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, refer to <c>PRECALC-FbLb67J5nL</c>.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-vF72Jwm0Jd-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49453/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>What is the right-hand limit of the function as <m>x</m> approaches 0?</li>
              <li>What is the left-hand limit of the function as <m>x</m> approaches 0?</li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li/>
              <li>does not exist</li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-8RIxt1s5uc-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49453/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>The position function <m>s(t)=-16t^{2}+144t</m> gives the position of a projectile as a function of time. Find the average velocity (average rate of change) on the interval <m>[1,2]</m>.</li>
            <li>The height of a projectile is given by <m>s(t)=-64t^{2}+192t</m> Find the average rate of change of the height from <m>t=1</m> second to <m>t=1.5</m> seconds.</li>
            <li>The amount of money in an account after <m>t</m> years compounded continuously at 4.25% interest is given by the formula <m>A=A_{0}e^{0.0425t},</m> where <m>A_{0}</m> is the initial amount invested. Find the average rate of change of the balance of the account from <m>t=1</m> year to <m>t=2</m> years if the initial amount invested is $1,000.00.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li/>
            <li>52</li>
            <li/>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-3bavaSEF2H" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given that <m>h^{-1}(6)=2,</m> what are the corresponding input and output values of the original function <m>h?</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>h(2)=6</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-L10OVSQb1U" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>f(x)=x^{3}-4</m> and <m>g(x)=\sqrt[3]{x+4},</m> is <m>g=f^{-1}?</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Yes</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-WeT8Z4paVR" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>f(x)=(x-1)^{3}\text{ and }g(x)=\sqrt[3]{x}+1,</m> is <m>g=f^{-1}?</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Yes</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-z5LEpBWoWz" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>The domain of function <m>f</m> is <m>(1,∞)</m> and the range of function <m>f</m> is <m>(−∞,−2).</m> Find the domain and range of the inverse function.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The domain of function <m>f^{-1}</m> is <m>(-∞\text{ , }-2)</m> and the range of function <m>f^{-1}</m> is <m>(1,∞).</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-hbD7AxIZJQ" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Using <xref ref="PRECALC-kjBm04KB6H" />, find and interpret (a) <m>f(60),</m> and (b) <m>f^{-1}(60).</m>
        </p>
        <table xml:id="PRECALC-kjBm04KB6H" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell>
                <m>t\text{ (minutes) }</m>
              </cell>
              <cell>30</cell>
              <cell>50</cell>
              <cell>60</cell>
              <cell>70</cell>
              <cell>90</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                <m>f(t)\text{ (miles) }</m>
              </cell>
              <cell>20</cell>
              <cell>40</cell>
              <cell>50</cell>
              <cell>60</cell>
              <cell>70</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>f(60)=50.</m> In 60 minutes, 50 miles are traveled.</li>
          <li>
            <m>f^{-1}(60)=70.</m> To travel 60 miles, it will take 70 minutes.</li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-UklQDmg7DI" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Using the graph in <xref ref="PRECALC-loY61qKAEE" />, (a) find <m>g^{-1}(1),</m> and (b) estimate <m>g^{-1}(4).</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>a. 3; b. 5.6</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-KXXlrBYmKx" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in terms of <m>y</m> given <m>y=\frac{1}{3}(x-5)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x=3y+5</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-JxfAdJo24p" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>What is the inverse of the function <m>f(x)=2-\sqrt{x}?</m> State the domains of both the function and the inverse function.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>f^{-1}(x)=(2-x)^{2};</m>
          <m>\text{ domain }\text{ of }f:[0,∞);</m>
          <m>\text{ domain }\text{ of }f^{-1}:(-∞,2]</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-FMIZ5OXnf3" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Draw graphs of the functions <m>f</m> and <m>f^{-1}</m> from <xref ref="PRECALC-OWPUCjnhqA" />.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <image xml:id="PRECALC-4O1BVjJsDL" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_01_07_012.jpg" width="80%">
          <description>
                       Graph of f(x) and f^(-1)(x).
                   </description>
        </image>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-kREd7L5BjS-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>Describe why the horizontal line test is an effective way to determine whether a function is one-to-one?</li>
            <li>Why do we restrict the domain of the function <m>f(x)=x^{2}</m> to find the function’s inverse?</li>
            <li>Can a function be its own inverse? Explain.</li>
            <li>Are one-to-one functions either always increasing or always decreasing? Why or why not?</li>
            <li>How do you find the inverse of a function algebraically?</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>Each output of a function must have exactly one output for the function to be one-to-one. If any horizontal line crosses the graph of a function more than once, that means that <m>y</m>-values repeat and the function is not one-to-one. If no horizontal line crosses the graph of the function more than once, then no <m>y</m>-values repeat and the function is one-to-one.</li>
            <li/>
            <li>Yes. For example, <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x}</m> is its own inverse.</li>
            <li/>
            <li>Given a function <m>y=f(x),</m> solve for <m>x</m> in terms of <m>y.</m> Interchange the <m>x</m> and <m>y.</m> Solve the new equation for <m>y.</m> The expression for <m>y</m> is the inverse, <m>y=f^{-1}(x).</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-FMmONHtgTk" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>Show that the function <m>f(x)=a-x</m> is its own inverse for all real numbers <m>a.</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, find <m>f^{-1}(x)</m> for each function.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-hJ6tEP7REp-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=x+3</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=x+5</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=2-x</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=3-x</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{x+2}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=\frac{2x+3}{5x+4}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f^{-1}(x)=x-3</m>
              </li>
              <li/>
              <li>
                <m>f^{-1}(x)=2-x</m>
              </li>
              <li/>
              <li>
                <m>f^{-1}(x)=\frac{-2x}{x-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li/>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, find a domain on which each function <m>f</m> is one-to-one and non-decreasing. Write the domain in interval notation. Then find the inverse of <m>f</m> restricted to that domain.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-QVBJpyqEdR-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=(x+7)^{2}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=(x-6)^{2}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=x^{2}-5</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>domain of <m>f(x):[-7,∞);f^{-1}(x)=\sqrt{x}-7</m>
              </li>
              <li/>
              <li>domain of <m>f(x):[0,∞);f^{-1}(x)=\sqrt{x+5}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-WcM6QqPTve" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <p>Given <m>f(x)=\frac{x}{2+x}</m> and <m>g(x)=\frac{2x}{1-x}:</m>
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>Find <m>f(g(x))</m> and <m>g(f(x)).</m>
              </li>
              <li>What does the answer tell us about the relationship between <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)?</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f(g(x))=x</m> and <m>g(f(x))=x.</m>
              </li>
              <li>This tells us that <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are inverse functions</li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, use function composition to verify that <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are inverse functions.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-tI9lD9WVeY-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x-1}</m> and <m>g(x)=x^{3}+1</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>f(x)=-3x+5</m> and <m>g(x)=\frac{x-5}{-3}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>f(g(x))=x,g(f(x))=x</m>
              </li>
              <li/>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
