          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f(−2)</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f(a)</m>
            </li>
            <li>Show that the function <m>f(x)=-2(x-1)^{2}+3</m> is not one-to-one.</li>
            <li>Write the domain of the function <m>f(x)=\sqrt{3-x}</m> in interval notation.</li>
            <li>Given <m>f(x)=2x^{2}-5x,</m> find <m>f(a+1)-f(1).</m>
            </li>
            <li>Graph the function</li>
            <p>
              <me>f(x)=\begin{cases} x+1\text{ if }  -2  x  3 \\ -x\text{ if }  x \ge 3 \end{cases}</me>
            </p>
            <li>Find the average rate of change of the function <m>f(x)=3-2x^{2}+x</m> by finding <m>\frac{f(b)-f(a)}{b-a}.</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>−16</li>
            <li/>
            <li>The graph is a parabola and the graph fails the horizontal line test.</li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>2a^{2}-a</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>-2(a+b)+1</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-bsA7PfpGhe-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>(g∘f)(x)</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>(g∘f)(1)</m>
            </li>
            <li>Express <m>H(x)=\sqrt[3]{5x^{2}-3x}</m> as a composition of two functions, <m>f</m> and <m>g,</m> where <m>(f∘g)(x)=H(x).</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>\sqrt{2}</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-vGVdrbohAS-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt{x+6}-1</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x+2}-1</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-L0Yj7L6Csc-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=-\frac{5}{x^{2}}+9x^{6}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=-\frac{5}{x^{3}}+9x^{5}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x}</m>
            </li>
            <li>Graph the absolute value function <m>f(x)=-2|x-1|+3.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Solve <m>|2x-3|=17.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Solve <m>-|\frac{1}{3}x-3| \ge 17.</m> Express the solution in interval notation.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>\text{ even }</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>\text{ odd }</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>x=-7</m> and <m>x=10</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-ZWaAytr0j2-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=3x-5</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>f(x)=\frac{4}{x+7}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f^{-1}(x)=\frac{x+5}{3}</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-GFeaSDn0Bz-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>On what intervals is the function increasing?</li>
            <li>On what intervals is the function decreasing?</li>
            <li>Approximate the local minimum of the function. Express the answer as an ordered pair. The ordered pair should include both the <m>x</m> value as well as the <m>g(x)</m> value.</li>
            <li>Approximate the local maximum of the function. Express the answer as an ordered pair. The ordered pair should include both the <m>x</m> value as well as the <m>g(x)</m> value.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>(-∞,-1.1)\text{ and }(1.1,∞)</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>(1.1,-0.9)</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-lVVv2Ciqsy-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Find <m>f(2).</m>
            </li>
            <li>Find <m>f(−2).</m>
            </li>
            <li>Write an equation for the piecewise function.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
              <m>f(2)=2</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <me>f(x)=\begin{cases} |x|\text{ if }x \le 2 \\ 3\text{ if }x  2 \end{cases}</me>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-WGDTIy4Tfe-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>Find <m>f(6).</m>
            </li>
            <li>Solve the equation <m>f(x)=5.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Is the graph increasing or decreasing on its domain?</li>
            <li>Is the function represented by the graph one-to-one?</li>
            <li>Find <m>f^{-1}(15).</m>
            </li>
            <li>Given <m>f(x)=-2x+11,</m> find <m>f^{-1}(x).</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>x=2</m>
            </li>
            <li/>
            <li>yes</li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>f^{-1}(x)=-\frac{x-11}{2}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-l733jKY1s1-parts-v2" original="PRECALC/modules/m49320/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>To convert from <m>x</m> degrees Celsius to <m>y</m> degrees Fahrenheit, we use the formula <m>f(x)=\frac{9}{5}x+32.</m> Find the inverse function, if it exists, and explain its meaning.</li>
            <li>The circumference <m>C</m> of a circle is a function of its radius given by <m>C(r)=2πr.</m> Express the radius of a circle as a function of its circumference. Call this function <m>r(C).</m> Find <m>r(36π)</m> and interpret its meaning.</li>
            <li>A car travels at a constant speed of 50 miles per hour. The distance the car travels in miles is a function of time, <m>t,</m> in hours given by <m>d(t)=50t.</m> Find the inverse function by expressing the time of travel in terms of the distance traveled. Call this function <m>t(d).</m> Find <m>t(180)</m> and interpret its meaning.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>
              <m>f^{-1}(x)=\frac{5}{9}(x-32).</m> Given the Fahrenheit temperature, <m>x,</m> this formula allows you to calculate the Celsius temperature.</li>
            <li/>
            <li>
              <m>t(d)=\frac{d}{50},</m>
              <m>t(180)=\frac{180}{50}.</m> The time for the car to travel 180 miles is 3.6 hours.</li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
  </exercises>

